ent |last1=Feyel|first1=Juliette |journal=\u00c9tudes Lawrenciennes |volume=45 |issue= |year=2014 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=D.H. Lawrence's plural jurisprudence: an enquiry into Desmond Manderson's post-positivist 'law and literature' |last1=G\u00f3mez Romero|first1=Luis |journal=Griffith Law Review |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=232\u2013260|year=2014 |doi=10.1080/10383441.2014.962681 |ref=harv|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2952&context=lhapapers }} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The Plumed Serpent/Lawrence and Nietzsche: A Study in Influence/The Spirit of D. H. Lawrence: Centenary Studies |last1=Hewitt|first1=Karen McLeod |journal=[[The Review of English Studies]] |volume=40 |issue=160 |pages=588\u2013590|year=1989 |doi=10.1093/res/XL.160.588 |jstor=517134 |ref=harv}} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal |title=La funci\u00f3n textual del espacio topogr\u00e1fico en \"The plumed serpent\", de D. H. Lawrence |last1=Le\u00f3n-Real M\u00e9ndez|first1=Nora Marisa |journal=Signa: Revista de la Asociaci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola de Semi\u00f3tica |volume=23 |issue= |year=2014 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=D. H. Lawrence's \"Dark Page\": Narrative Primitivism in Women in Love and The Plumed Serpent |last1=Neilson|first1=Brett |journal=Twentieth Century Literature |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=310|year=1997 |doi= 10.2307/441914|ref=harv|jstor=441914}}\n* {{cite journal |title=An Introduction to Neonativist Collectives: Place, Not Race, in Cather's The Professor's House and Lawrence's The Plumed Serpent |last1=Newmark|first1=Julianne |journal=Arizona Quarterly |volume=66 |issue=2 |year=2010 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=D. H. Lawrence. M\u00e9xico, la utop\u00eda imposible |last1=Pereira|first1=Armando |journal=Literatura Mexicana |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=65\u201390|year=2013 |doi=10.1016/S0188-2546(13)71739-2 |ref=harv|doi-access=free }} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=D. H. Lawrence's The Plumed Serpent: The Dialectic of Ideology and Utopia |last1=Przybylowicz|first1=Donna |journal=[[Boundary 2]] |volume=13 |issue=2/3 |year=1985 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Messianism and the Abject: Reading D. H. Lawrence's The Plumed Serpent |last1=Raghinaru|first1=Camelia |journal=Studies in the Novel |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=20\u201343|year=2014 |doi=10.1353/sdn.2014.0029 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=D.H. Lawrence en M\u00e9xico: la inveros\u00edmil transformaci\u00f3n del hombre en mito |last1=Rivas Iturralde|first1=Vladimiro |journal=Fuentes Human\u00edsticas |volume=29 |issue=55 |year=2017 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=V\u00f6lkisch Organicism and the Use of Primitivism in Lawrence's \"The Plumed Serpent\" |last1=Smith|first1=Jad |journal=The D. H. Lawrence Review |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2002 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=\"The Plumed Serpent\" and The Eternal Paradox |last1=Vickery|first1=John B. |journal=Criticism |volume=5 |issue=2 |year=1963 |doi= |ref=harv|jstor=41938335?seq=1}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Recommended reading |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |volume=7 |issue=13 |year=1926 |doi= |ref={{harvid|Time|1926}}}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Online articles\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Krauze|first1=Enrique |url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/11/british-writers-mecico-night-day-dh-lawrence-graham-greene-rebecca-west | title = British writers on Mexico's 'night' of violence and 'day' of magical attraction |date=April 11, 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate = 23 June 2017 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Torgovnick|first1=Marianna |url = https://www.chronicle.com/article/Our-DH-Lawrence-Moment/229767/?cid=aldaily-cr-teaser | title = Our D.H. Lawrence Moment |date=May 4, 2015 |work=[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]] |accessdate = 17 April 2017 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://castle.eiu.edu/~agora/Dec03/JSmithall.htm V\u00f6lkisch Organicism and the Use of Primitivism in Lawrence\u2019s The Plumed Serpent]\n\n{{D. H. Lawrence}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plumed Serpent}}\n[[Category:1926 British novels]]\n[[Category:Alfred A. Knopf books]]\n[[Category:Aztecs in fiction]]\n[[Category:British political novels]]\n[[Category:English novels]]\n[[Category:Martin Secker books]]\n[[Category:Novels about religion]]\n[[Category:Novels by D. H. Lawrence]]\n", "name_user": "Cyfal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling (Wikipedia:Typo Team)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Plumed_Serpent"}
{"title_page": "2003 Nova Scotia general election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2003 Nova Scotia general election\n| country            = Nova Scotia\n| type               = parliamentary\n| party_colour       = no\n| party_name         = no\n| previous_election  = 1999 Nova Scotia general election\n| previous_year      = 1999\n| previous_mps       = 58th General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| election_date      = August 5, 2003\n| elected_mps        = [[59th General Assembly of Nova Scotia|members]]\n| next_election      = 2006 Nova Scotia general election\n| next_year          = 2006\n| next_mps           = 60th General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| seats_for_election = 52 seats of the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] | majority_seats = 27 \n| image1             = [[Image:Jhamm03election.JPG|150x150px]]\n| colour1            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|nohash}}\n| leader1            = [[John Hamm]]\n| leader_since1      = [[Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia leadership elections#1995 leadership convention|October 28, 1995]]\n| party1             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| leaders_seat1      = [[Pictou Centre]]\n| last_election1     = 30\n| seats1             = 25\n| seat_change1       = {{decrease}}5\n| popular_vote1      = 148,182\n| percentage1        = 36.32%\n| swing1             = {{decrease}}2.88%\n| image2             = [[Image:Darrell Dexter 2.jpg|150x150px]]\n| colour2            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|nohash}}\n| leader2            = [[Darrell Dexter]]\n| leader_since2      = [[Nova Scotia New Democratic Party leadership elections#2002 leadership convention|June 2, 2002]]\n| party2             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|name}}\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Cole Harbour (electoral district)|Cole Harbour]]\n| last_election2     = 11\n| seats2             = 15\n| seat_change2       = {{increase}}4\n| popular_vote2      = 126,479\n| percentage2        = 31.00%\n| swing2             = {{increase}}1.03%\n| image3             = \n<div style=\"width:115px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''LIB''' </span></div>\n| colour3            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|nohash}}\n| leader3            = [[Danny Graham (Halifax MLA)|Danny Graham]]\n| leader_since3      = [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party leadership elections#2002 leadership convention|April 13, 2002]]\n| party3             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|name}}\n| leaders_seat3      = [[Halifax Citadel-Sable Island|Halifax Citadel]]\n| last_election3     = 11\n| seats3             = 12\n| seat_change3       = {{increase}}1\n| popular_vote3      = 128,417\n| percentage3        = 31.47%\n| swing3             = {{increase}}1.66%\n| map_image          = Nova Scotia general election, 2003 results by riding.svg\n| map_size           = 400px\n| map_caption        = Popular vote by riding. As this is an FPTP election, seat totals are not determined by popular vote, but instead via results by each riding.\n| title              = Premier\n| before_election    = [[John Hamm]]\n| before_party       = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| after_election     = John Hamm\n| posttitle          = Premier after election\n| after_party        = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n}}\nThe '''2003 Nova Scotia general election''' was held on August 5, 2003 to elect members of the [[59th General Assembly of Nova Scotia|59th House of Assembly]] of the Province of [[Nova Scotia]], Canada. The ruling [[Nova Scotia Progressive Conservative Party|Progressive Conservative Party]], led by Premier [[John Hamm]], was reduced to a [[minority government]].\n\n==Campaign==\nThe election was called by Progressive Conservatives, who decided to hold a rare summer election in the hope of strengthening their hold on the legislature.  Running against them were the [[Nova Scotia New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party]] (NDP), led by [[Darrell Dexter]], and the [[Liberal Party of Nova Scotia|Liberal Party]], led by [[Danny Graham (Halifax MLA)|Danny Graham]].\n\nHamm's party ran on a policy of fiscal management, [[tax cut]]s, and on their record of fulfilling most of their promises. While the NDP agreed in principle to tax cuts, their main cause was the creation of a public [[auto insurance]] company. The Liberals were the only party to criticize the tax cuts.\n\nFor the most part, the campaign was quiet and uneventful.  Hamm received criticism for a great number of spending programs, including a $150 tax rebate cheque sent to Nova Scotians right before the election.  The party was also criticized for holding an election in the summer when most people have other concerns.  Darrell Dexter's friendly, non-confrontational style, was popular with many voters, and was a marked change from his party's usually strident socialism.  Danny Graham, a young leader, was popular, but failed to make much of a mark.\n\nThe election was considered a mild failure for the Liberals and Progressive \nConservatives, and something of a success for the NDP.\n\nThis election is also notable for being one of the last Canadian provincial elections in which [[British subject]]s could vote (a tiny number can still vote provincially in [[Saskatchewan]] if they were qualified in 1971).<ref>[https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20030707003 Voters' List Being Prepared In New Way] Nova Scotia Government</ref>\n\n==General results==\n\n===Results by party===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border-color: #444444\"\n|- bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Party leader\n!rowspan=\"2\"|# of<br />candidates\n!colspan=\"4\"|Seats\n!colspan=\"3\"|Popular vote\n|- bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"\n|align=\"center\"|[[1999 Nova Scotia general election|1999]]\n|align=\"center\"|<span style=\"font-size: 75%;\">[[Dissolution of parliament|Dissolution]