{"title_page": "Denise White", "text_new": "{{short description|Chief executive officer of EAG Sports Management, Miss Oregon USA 1994, Congeniality Award at Miss USA 1994}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Undisclosed paid|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| photo = \n| birth_name=Denise White\n| occupation = {{nowrap|[[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of EAG Sports Management}}\n| years active = 1996\u2013present\n| title=[[Miss Oregon USA|Miss Oregon USA 1994]]\n| nationalcompetition= [[Miss Oregon USA|Miss Oregon USA 1994]]<br>(Winner)<br>(Miss Congeniality)<br>[[Miss USA 1994]]<br>(Miss Congeniality)\n| birth_place = [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[California]]\n| homepage = http://www.eagsportsmanagement.com/about-eag.html\n}}\n'''Denise White''' is a former [[Miss Oregon USA]] who founded EAG Sports Management, a sports firm for high-end athletes.\n\n==Miss Oregon USA==\nBorn in [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[California]], White represented [[Miss Oregon USA|Oregon]] in the 1994 [[Miss USA 1994#Special awards|Miss USA]] pageant, broadcast live from [[South Padre Island, Texas|South Padre Island]], [[Texas]] on February 11, 1994, where she obtained the Congeniality Award, an honor she had previously received while competing for the [[Miss Oregon USA]] title.<ref name=union>{{cite news|title=Escondido grad will have plenty of say in Evert Cup|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=February 28, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Sports management career==\nWhite is the [[CEO]] and founder of her own sports firm, EAG Sports Management, which represents several high-end sports clients, which included her first client of fourteen years, eleven-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection and NFL Hall of Famer, Tony Gonzalez. [[Kellen Winslow II]] who [[Kellen Winslow II#2008_season|appealed]] a suspension from [[Cleveland Browns]]' GM [[Phil Savage]] after Winslow criticized the team's handling of his hospitalization with [[staph infection]];<ref name=winslow>{{cite news|title=Browns TE Winslow appeals suspension|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/2008-10-24-1014095506_x.htm|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=October 24, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>  and [[defensive end]] for the [[Minnesota Vikings]] [[Jared Allen]] who has had some [[Jared Allen#Legal troubles|legal troubles]] and personally contributed $2500, along with White who donated another $2500, to an animal shelter for information leading to the arrest and conviction of the person responsible for abandoning a starving horse in LA.<ref name=allen>{{cite news|title=Jared Allen threatens bar patron|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/91601814.html|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=April 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529054746/http://www.startribune.com/local/91601814.html|archive-date=29 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=allen2>{{cite news|title=Minnesota Vikings star Jared Allen raises reward to $7500|url=http://seaaca.org/jared%20allen%20reward%20horse%20abuse.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=seaaca.org/|date=August 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128102319/http://seaaca.org/jared%20allen%20reward%20horse%20abuse.pdf|archivedate=28 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2016 it was announced by FOX2000 that a motion picture starring [[Jennifer Aniston]] portraying Denise White was in production for shooting in 2017. It is called \"The Fixer\". In 2018, White signed a deal with Apple and Jennifer Aniston's production company to develop a TV drama based on White's life and work.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eagsportsmanagement.com/about-eag.html EAG Sports Management]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Massachusetts}} Stacey Blaine|}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Miss USA - Congeniality Award\n|years=[[Miss USA 1994#Special awards|1994]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|{{flagicon|Texas}} [[Chelsi Smith]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Denise}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n[[Category:Miss USA 1994 delegates]]\n[[Category:People from Escondido, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Undisclosed paid|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| photo = \n| birth_name=Denise White\n| occupation = {{nowrap|[[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of EAG Sports Management}}\n| years active = 1996\u2013present\n| title=[[Miss Oregon USA|Miss Oregon USA 1994]]\n| nationalcompetition= [[Miss Oregon USA|Miss Oregon USA 1994]]<br>(Winner)<br>(Miss Congeniality)<br>[[Miss USA 1994]]<br>(Miss Congeniality)\n| birth_place = [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[California]]\n| homepage = http://www.eagsportsmanagement.com/about-eag.html\n}}\n'''Denise White''' is a former [[Miss Oregon USA]] who founded EAG Sports Management, a sports firm for high-end athletes.\n\n==Miss Oregon USA==\nBorn in [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[California]], White represented [[Miss Oregon USA|Oregon]] in the 1994 [[Miss USA 1994#Special awards|Miss USA]] pageant, broadcast live from [[South Padre Island, Texas|South Padre Island]], [[Texas]] on February 11, 1994, where she obtained the Congeniality Award, an honor she had previously received while competing for the [[Miss Oregon USA]] title.<ref name=union>{{cite news|title=Escondido grad will have plenty of say in Evert Cup|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=February 28, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Sports management career==\nWhite is the [[CEO]] and founder of her own sports firm, EAG Sports Management, which represents several high-end sports clients, which included her first client of fourteen years, eleven-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection and NFL Hall of Famer, Tony Gonzalez. [[Kellen Winslow II]] who [[Kellen Winslow II#2008_season|appealed]] a suspension from [[Cleveland Browns]]' GM [[Phil Savage]] after Winslow criticized the team's handling of his hospitalization with [[staph infection]];<ref name=winslow>{{cite news|title=Browns TE Winslow appeals suspension|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/2008-10-24-1014095506_x.htm|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=October 24, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>  and [[defensive end]] for the [[Minnesota Vikings]] [[Jared Allen]] who has had some [[Jared Allen#Legal troubles|legal troubles]] and personally contributed $2500, along with White who donated another $2500, to an animal shelter for information leading to the arrest and conviction of the person responsible for abandoning a starving horse in LA.<ref name=allen>{{cite news|title=Jared Allen threatens bar patron|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/91601814.html|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=April 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529054746/http://www.startribune.com/local/91601814.html|archive-date=29 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=allen2>{{cite news|title=Minnesota Vikings star Jared Allen raises reward to $7500|url=http://seaaca.org/jared%20allen%20reward%20horse%20abuse.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2011|newspaper=seaaca.org/|date=August 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128102319/http://seaaca.org/jared%20allen%20reward%20horse%20abuse.pdf|archivedate=28 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2016 it was announced by FOX2000 that a motion picture starring [[Jennifer Aniston]] portraying Denise White was in production for shooting in 2017. It is called \"The Fixer\". In 2018, White signed a deal with Apple and Jennifer Aniston's production company to develop a TV drama based on White's life and work.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eagsportsmanagement.com/about-eag.ht